## The Writing

### ONCE — The Mythology

Six original creation myths forming the cosmology of a fantasy world. This is his current primary writing project, being developed in a year-long writing workshop called Analog with Ravi Gupta (host of Lost Debate podcast, author of Garbage Town). He joined the class for free after reconnecting with Ravi in Costa Rica.

The myths have been in development for over two years, including throughout his time at SKIMS. He is ashamed of how long they've taken but confident he will finish them this year in Ravi's class.

What the myths actually are: not worldbuilding in the conventional fantasy sense. He's built a complete moral philosophy that answers the questions every civilization must answer — What are we for? What is evil? What happens when we die? What do we owe each other? — and followed each answer to its consequences, including the ugly ones. The civilization document covers gender, death, value, labor, sex, slavery, suicide, ecology, governance. Every piece flows from the cosmology. It's load-bearing all the way down.

The reason the myths have taken so long is not that he was hiding from the novel. It's that the thing he's building is genuinely massive in scope, and he kept going deeper instead of drawing boundaries around what "done" means. He needs to finish the six texts as standalone pieces this year and let the civilization document keep breathing as a living reference.

He feels that modern religions and societies have failed to provide him with a sufficient "why" for anything. So he invented a society that has a why and is showing its pros and cons. This is the engine of the whole project.

The myths started as foundation for Only Us. They've grown into something bigger than scaffolding. They are his differentiator as a creator — what makes him different from every other fantasy content creator who reviews and ranks other people's work. They are the brand's primary shareable content until the novel exists.

### Only Us

A fantasy trilogy. His primary book project. Reimagines Joseph from Genesis as Zoh Orr, a king's daughter who ascends despite betrayal. Set in the world built by ONCE.

Only Us feels disconnected from the myths right now and very far away. He has decided — correctly — to finish the myths first and then see what's true, rather than trying to plan the novel while the myths are still unfinished. The disconnection may just be honesty: he's been living inside cosmology and theology for two years, and a novel about a character is a different muscle. The bridge will likely be there when he needs it.

### Kept — The First Trilogy (Retired)

The complete documented history spans May 2017 to May 12, 2023. Six years.

Kept was a fantasy trilogy. Evan wrote the first book and a trilogy outline. The querying campaign was genuinely extraordinary in scope: at least 14 publishers, 20+ individual editors, multiple full manuscript requests from the largest publishers on earth. Formal CAA coverage for adaptation. Paradigm Talent Agency. UTA media rights. WME. The CEO of Penguin Random House replied personally with his cell number. A map commissioned from an artist in Ireland for $100 that every single person mentioned. A scientist consulted on a compound that doesn't exist for the worldbuilding.

He landed an agent (Brendan, at Assemble Media) in December 2019. Three dream literary agents passed on the same day. The agent relationship lasted until June 2021 when Brendan left Assemble for Blackstone Publishing. By Evan's own later admission, he never truly felt The Keeper was in the right hands.

The book had a consistent problem that multiple independent readers identified — worldbuilding that didn't feel distinct enough, information that was hard to follow, a structure that felt inaccessible. At the time, Evan often reframed this as the industry being locked into a YA lens. Six years of the same note from completely different people across Hollywood and publishing is worth sitting with.

Retired May 12, 2023. His retirement letter to the 40 people who read it: "The Keeper, as it is known to you, will never be printed or queried again; it will forever be ours and ours alone. And although I consider The Keeper's radical minimalism a failed experiment, sharing it with you has imbued me with a purity of patient purpose previously incomprehensible."

He retired it on his own terms. His standards, not theirs. That's integrity, not failure.

The Outside Inn — the community gathering place that now anchors the entire EIW brand — first appeared as a backwoods tavern in the prequel to the book nobody published. The fiction preceded the brand.

### The Marathon Script

Co-written with Otis Blum (Jason Blum's half-brother). About the first marathon runner in ancient Athens. Currently out to directors and production companies via their manager, John Burnham, since the day after MLK Day 2026.

Evan carried this project. He did roughly 85% of the writing, convinced Otis of the opportunities, navigated the relationship, and pushed back on rushing it out before the holidays when he saw low-hanging improvements. He's genuinely proud of how the script turned out.

Earlier in the process, there were producers interested but it was conditional on one of them playing a lead and he was the wrong fit, so Evan and Otis backed out.

The script consumed September 2025 through mid-January 2026 — five months where the myths and Only Us didn't move much. It was real work and real experience, but it was also five months substantially devoted to someone else's vehicle. Going forward, he needs to be ruthless about how much time goes to projects where someone else holds the keys.

No word yet on any movement. He's starting to feel like it likely won't go anywhere, which may or may not be true. He always knew it was a long shot.

### Kinfire Chronicles: Night's Fall

Wrote quests for this tabletop game. Kickstarted, shipped to acclaim. Characters he created remain in the game after multiple expansions. Published, public, shareable freely.

