## The Carson Thatcher Situation

### What Happened

Carson Thatcher is Evan's friend of over a decade and a legitimate working producer/songwriter with credits on major releases. His market rate is $4k+/song. He was producing the music for Outside Inn at well below market rate as a favor to a friend.

The business negotiation escalated over email in early February 2026. Key sequence:

1. An AI assistant (Claude, in a previous conversation) advised Evan to lower the per-track cash payment from $500/track to $150/track and frame it as strategic restructuring rather than financial necessity.
2. Carson's manager had a great call with Evan on February 5 and the deal was essentially agreed at $3,000 for the album.
3. Hours after that call, Carson sent a warm, collaborative email ("Super hyped bro") with reasonable pushback on scope math.
4. The AI advised Evan to call the original $9k figure "an estimate, not a handshake deal" and to remove an apology Evan had instinctively included.
5. Evan sent a numbered list of scope corrections — clinical in tone, sent the morning after the deal was essentially closed.
6. Carson responded with a $15k spite counter, legal threats about master ownership, and passive-aggressive comments about Evan's travel lifestyle.
7. Evan tried calling. No answer. Over the next several days, he sent three increasingly honest and vulnerable text messages taking full ownership.
8. Carson responded: "On a friendship level it's cool. It wasn't about the money, it was about the way in which you switched it up and about your follow up email and ultimately respect."
9. Carson agreed to finish some tracks as a kindness, no money upfront, and end the ongoing business partnership.
10. As of February 16, Carson is sending completed deliverables and offering to call.

### What It Revealed

Evan's relational instincts were better than the AI's strategic advice at every turn. He wanted to apologize — the AI said remove it. He questioned the "estimate" framing after sending — the AI validated it. His drafts were warmer — the AI made them more clinical.

But Evan followed the advice. He chose the clinical framing over the warm one. He chose leverage over relationship. Under financial stress, he got transactional — the same pattern that showed up at SKIMS.

Carson wasn't an asshole situation. The email wasn't cruel or disrespectful in intent. It was a numbered list of scope corrections sent to a friend who had just written a warm, collaborative message. The mismatch in tone did the damage. Carson's response was disproportionate (legal threats, spite number, vacation comments) but his core read was correct.

The recovery worked because the foundation was real love. When Evan showed up as himself — the actual Evan, not the negotiator — Carson could meet him there.

**Key lesson:** When you love someone, lead with that. Especially when you're scared. Your relational instincts are better than your strategic instincts. When your gut says apologize, apologize.

### Current Status

Carson is finishing tracks as a favor. The business partnership is ending but the friendship survived. Evan needs to have a phone call with Carson to sort the business terms for the remaining deliverables before more work accumulates in ambiguity. He has explicitly learned not to negotiate over text or email with Carson.

